user_prompt: From 'If the whiffle was shanked, then the whiffle tinked', can we infer 'If the whiffle did not tink, then the whiffle was not shanked'?

responses.content: Yes, because the contrapositive of the statement "If the whiffle was shanked, then the whiffle tinked" is logically equivalent to "If the whiffle did not tink, then the whiffle was not shanked."
